Introduction ¶

Dataset Source ¶

The source of the dataset in this study is Kaggle (Ruchi Bhatia, June 2022). This dataset includes salaries of different data science jobs from 2020 to 2022 as well as other features such as experience level, employment type, and company size.

Dataset Details ¶

The dataset contains the salaries of data scientists in different data science jobs. It also includes the level of experience that they have, theirs and their company's location, and their remote ratio (i.e. if they work fully remote, partially, etc.). Other features that is included are the size of the company that they work in, another currency (aside form USD), and their salary in that currency.

There are 607 observations and 11 features in this dataset.

Response Variable ¶

For this study, the target feature will be the salary (i.e. salary_in_usd). Predictions will be made on this feature as a result of the explanatory/descriptive variables.

Goals & Objectives ¶

The Data Science Industry has a range of job salaries depending on different factors. It can be difficult to know which job will give a person the highest or most realistic salary, so being able to predict the try of salary depending on different factors such as company size and location will save many users the time and trouble of searching for the right job. A situation where this would be useful is if someone has been offered a position in a small company and would like to check the salary predictor to see what the average salary in a data science position might be in a smaller company. Likewise, if that person was also planning on being a full time employee, they can check if there is much difference (on average) between salaries for full time employees vs part time employees etc.

The focus and objective of this project will be: to predict the salaries of different job titles in the Data Science workforce determined on specific features such as job title, employment type or employee residence. Another goal/ objective is to ultimately find which of the many features are the most effective and accurate at predicting the salary. To achieve this, we aim to create a variety of data visualization plots to help visually represent and show the relevant data and to make informed decisions about which features are most effective at predicting the salary. Some data cleaning and preprocessing will also take place prior to, ensuring the data has been sifted through.

In this section, the dataset will be prepared for modelling. The whole process will be described below.

Check Current Features ¶

To start this off, we will first check the columns that are currently in the dataset, and drop the ones that are not necessary for modelling.

In [4]:
list(ds_data.columns)
Out[4]:
['work_year',
 'experience_level',
 'employment_type',
 'job_title',
 'salary',
 'salary_currency',
 'salary_in_usd',
 'employee_residence',
 'remote_ratio',
 'company_location',
 'company_size']

There are two features that are correlated to each other, one of which is correlated to another separate feature. The columns 'salary' and 'salary_in_usd' refer to the same numerical amount, but in different units (currency). Moreover, 'salary' is also connected to 'salary_currency', which describes the currency for the 'salary' feature.

For this reason, we will only keep the feature 'salary_in_usd' to maintain consistency as we only need one of the three correlated features. Hence, we will drop 'salary' and 'salary_currency'.

In [5]:
ds_data = ds_data.drop(columns = ['salary', 'salary_currency'])

Data Exploration & Visualisation

One-Variable Plots

Bar chart of Employment Type¶

The kick this all off, Figure 1 displays all the different Employment Types that Data Scientists are. The majority of these are Full Time employees, which fits in the with typical employee working a 9-5 full time job. This also diplays that for the all of the other data present, they are most likely a full time employee.

In [11]:

plt.ylabel('Count')
plt.title('Figure 1: Bar chart of Employment Type')
plt.show()

Bar chart of Remote Ratio¶

In Figure 2, the data overwhelming suggests that the majority of Data Science Employees are working 100% remotely. This, we believe, due to the data being collected in 2020, the year in which remote working from home recieved a massive uptick due to the Coronavirus.

The results in Figure 3 display the spread of workforce sizes for Data Science Employees. This data consists of the most common worksize being Medium, followed by Large and Small respectively. This highlights the trend that the Data Scientists work in a Medium to Large sized workplace.

Two-Variable Plots

Boxplot of Salary by Company Size¶

As seen in Figure 6's boxplot of salary by company size, the different sized companies, small, medium and large, are compared to the different salaries. It can be noted that the size of the company has a direct impact on the size of the salary. There are a couple of outliers, however, they still comply with the trend of 'the bigger the company size, the larger the salary is'.

Lineplot of Salary by Remote Ratio and Experience Level¶

We observe an increase in salary as remote ratio increases. Moreover, this observation is also clearer as the experience level is higher. Although an increase is observed overall, Mid-level, Senior-level, and Executive-level of experience actually has a decline from non-remote to partially-remote employees. The increase happens drastically from partially-remote to fully-remote categories where the salary is also above the non-remote category.

Bar Chart of Fully Remote Employees Per Work Year and Company Size¶

In Figure 14, there are no similary patterns between the different company sizes.

As for the count, small companies had more fully remote employees in 2021 compared to 2020. However, this then dropped in 2022 even below the count of 2020. As an overall percentage of all employees in that year, the percentage of fully remote employees decreased from 2020 to 2022.

For medium-sized companies, the number and percentage of fully remote employees increased throughout the years, with a drastic increase between 2021 and 2022.

For large companies, the number and percentage of fully remote employees increased slightly from 2020 to 2021. The number decreased slightly in 2022 but the percentage decreased significantly due to medium-sized companies having more employees going remote.

Summary & Conclusion¶

Data science and adjacent fields are a rapidly growing and complex industry, with the salaries to prove that it is a vital and sought-after practice looking towards the future. Our goal with the project is to analyse the trends in the salaries, compared to experience level and fields of particular data science genres. This will then help us determine a reliable way to predict salaries using specific features.

Firstly, we started Phase 1 with data cleaning and preprocessing by dropping the columnms that would not be necessary in this project which are the 'salary' and 'salary_currency'. The dataset was then checked for missing or unusual values, which returned no concerns. Overall, the dataset was already clean so there was not much changes necessary aside from dropping columns. The data and data types were as inteded and sampling was not needed as there are only about 600 observations in the dataset.

We generated a variety of graphic solutions to explore the data. We found that senior-level employees are the most commonnly hired, and employees were most commonly full-time, whereas those considered executive-level were significantly less in quantity. We also found that the overall median wage for a data scientist was around $100k USD. The salary tend to increase as the work year, company size, and experience level increases and employees who are working full time also tend to have a higher salary compared to those who are not.

Generally, employees were more likely to work remote during 2020 and 2021 and started to transition back to face to face work in 2022, however the outlier here is medium size companies who had a large percetage of people transfer to remote work. All forms of work show a slight increase over time, however part-online, part-face to face shows the lowest increase out of all the options. Fully remote employees also tend to have made more than other employees who work partially-remote or not remote at all.
